In this notebook, we will be working with industry variables, using column graphs to visualize how the nature of work changed between 1870 and 1930. You will learn all the skills you need to complete Lab 4:

  • Using the grammar of graphics to control the appearance of your visualizations
  • Making publication-quality column graphs that display multiple variables
  • Recoding variables into a smaller number of categories
  • Grouping and summarizing your data frame

Exploring the data

Read in this weeks data as a data frame called ipums.

library(tidyverse)
ipums <- read_csv("wk4.csv")

Explore the dataset and documentation to determine which samples and variables we are working with.

names(ipums)
 [1] "YEAR"     "STATEFIP" "PERWT"    "SEX"      "AGE"      "RACE"     "RACED"    "OCC"      "OCC1950"  "IND1950" 
qplot(PERWT, data = ipums, facets = ~YEAR)

Grammar of graphics

We have already made some quick-and-dirty histograms using the qplot() function. Those are great for exploratory data analysis, but if we are going to use data visualizations to tell stories or make arguments, we will need to have more control over those visualizations. The ggplot() function gives us that control. To see how this function differs from qplot(), start by using qplot() to make histograms of AGE for each value of YEAR. Use binwidth = 5 and dont forget to weight.

qplot(PERWT,data=ipums,facets = ~AGE,binwidth=5)

The following code makes the same graph using the ggplot() function. We saw this function before when we made a jittered scatterplot.

ggplot(ipums, aes(AGE, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) + facet_wrap(vars(YEAR))

The ggplot() function allows you to use the grammar of graphics to control every aspect of your plot. You can make almost any kind of graph with the ggplot() function, so learning how it works will get you very far in the world of data visualization. It is rapidly becoming a standard for visualizing data in R. At a minimum, ggplot() requires three things: a data frame, an aesthetics (aes()) mapping, and a geometry (geom) layer. The variables you are visualizing go into the aes() mapping. By default, R will plot the first variable you name on the x-axis. If you name a second variable, R will plot it on the y-axis. Later on in this notebook, we will look at ways to visualize more than two variables. The first argument to ggplot() is the name of the data frame. Since ggplot() is part of the tidyverse, you can also omit this argument and pipe a data frame into the ggplot() function. The aes() mapping can go in many different places, but for now we will include it as the second argument to ggplot(). Run the following code.

Why did we get a blank graph? We specified that we wanted to visualize the ipums data frame with the AGE variable on the x-axis, with values weighted by PERWT. But we didnt tell ggplot how to visualize AGE. For that we need to add a geom() layer, which we do by literally adding it with a +. Here we specify that we want a histogram with a bin width of 5.

ggplot(ipums, aes(AGE, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

To facet the plot, we simply add a faceting layer. We have two options: facet_wrap() facets by one variable, and if there are more facets than will fit on a line, wraps to the next line (we can also indicate how many rows or columns of facets we want); facet_grid() facets only in the vertical or horizontal dimension, or both if you want to facet by two variables. Above we used facet_wrap(). Here we will use facet_grid().

ggplot(ipums, aes(AGE, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) + facet_grid(cols = vars(YEAR))

We can also facet vertically instead of horizontally.

ggplot(ipums, aes(AGE, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) + facet_grid(rows = vars(YEAR))

The ggplot() function produces an object that we can save. Once we have saved it, we can re-print it or add more layers to it. Lets save our basic age histogram, without facets, as agehist.

agehist <- ggplot(ipums, aes(AGE, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

Notice that there is no output to this code, since we created a variable (agehist) and assigned it a value (the histogram). If we want to print the graph, we can just do this:

agehist

If we want to facet by SEX as well as YEAR, we can put both variables in the facet_grid() layer. We can add this to our agehist object.

agehist + facet_grid(rows = vars(YEAR), cols = vars(SEX))

We can factor SEX right in the facet_grid() function to get better labels for our plot.

agehist + facet_grid(rows = vars(YEAR), cols = vars(factor(SEX, labels=c("Male","Female"))))

Lets save a smaller plot that we can keep working with: a histogram of AGE in 1880 only, faceted horizontally by SEX.

age_1880 <- ipums %>% filter (YEAR == 1880) %>%
  ggplot (aes(AGE,weight = PERWT)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
  facet_grid(cols=vars(factor(SEX,label=c("Male", "Female"))))
age_1880

There is still a lot we can do to make our plot more readable and attractive. We do this by adding more layers. We can change the overall look of our plot with a theme() function.

age_1880 + theme_bw()

age_1880 + theme_classic()

age_1880 + theme_minimal()

We can control various aspects of our axes. Here we use the scale_x_continuous() function to control the minimum and maximum values of the x-axis and to indicate which values we want to show on that axis, and we use the scale_y_continuous() function to format the numbers in the y-axis.

age_1880 + theme_minimal() + 
  scale_x_continuous(lim = c(0,100), breaks = c(25, 50, 75)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(label = scales::comma)

The warning tells us that not all of our observations were within the limits we set.

We can use the labs() function to change our axis labels and add a title.

age_1880 + theme_minimal() + 
  scale_x_continuous(lim = c(0,100)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(label = scales::comma) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Number of People", title = "Age Distribution by Sex, 1880")

Adding color

There are other ways to visualize the age distribution over time. We could make a bar graph with YEAR on the x-axis and total number of people on the y-axis, with the color of the bars representing people of each age. We will get there step by step.

What is the difference between these two plots?

ggplot(ipums, aes(YEAR, weight = PERWT)) + geom_histogram()

ggplot(ipums, aes(YEAR, weight = PERWT)) + geom_bar()

With ggplot(ipums, aes(YEAR, weight = PERWT)) + geom_bar(), we fed our whole ipums data frame into ggplot() and let ggplot() calculate the number of people, weighting by PERWT. Alternatively, we could have done that ourselves in a previous step, using two new dplyr functions: group_by() and count().

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR) %>% count(wt = PERWT)

This command says, for the ipums data frame, for each unique value of YEAR, count the number of records, weighting by PERWT. In the resulting data frame, n refers to the number of people in each given year. We can pipe this right into ggplot() or we can save it as a new data frame and then put it into ggplot().

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR)) + geom_bar()

This is not what we were expecting! The geom_bar() function counts the number of records for each year in the data frame, which in this case is 1. Instead, we want to use the geom_col() function, which lets us specify a variable for the y-axis.

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR, n)) + geom_col()

So why go through all of this extra trouble? Because we can use the same general principles to add additional variables to our graph. To color the columns by age, we add AGE to our group_by() function, and specify an aesthetic for it in the ggplot() function. We will assign it to the fill aesthetic, which refers to the color of an object (not to be confused with the color aesthetic, which refers to the color of an objects outline). As you will see here, the default outline is gray.

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR, AGE) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR, n, fill = AGE)) + geom_col()

We can add all of our other layers to make the plot look good.

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR, AGE) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR, n, fill = AGE)) + geom_col() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1870, 1880, 1900, 1910, 1920, 1930)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(x = "Census Year", y = "Population", fill = "Age", title = "U.S. Population by Age, 1870-1930")

If we want to facet by sex, we will need to make a data frame that includes one row for each combination of YEAR, AGE, and SEX. We can do this by adding SEX to the group_by() function. Then we just add a facet_grid() layer to the ggplot() function. Paste in the code from the graph above and make those changes. Be sure to include the value labels for SEX.

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR, AGE, SEX) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR, n, fill = AGE)) + geom_col() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1870, 1880, 1900, 1910, 1920, 1930)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
     facet_grid(cols=vars(factor(SEX,label=c("Male", "Female"))))

    theme_minimal() +
    labs(x = "Census Year", y = "Population", fill = "Age", title = "U.S. Population by Age, 1870-1930")

Recoding Industry

This plot of IND1950 is not very informative. It made sense to plot AGE on a continuous color scale because age is a numeric variable, but industry is a categorical variable. IND1950 has too many values to make sense of individually, so lets group them together into categories. Look at the documentation for IND1950 to see how I chose these categories. This recoding process is very similar to the process we used last week to recode RACE and RACED, but there we were doing a one-to-one recode (one value of the old variable converted to each value of the new variable) and here we are doing a many-to-one recode (many values of the old variable convert to each value of the new variable). For that reason, it is easier to do the recode in two steps: the first step supplies the new numeric values and the second converts it to a factor and adds labels.

ipums <- ipums %>%
          mutate(IND = ifelse(IND1950 == 0 | IND1950 >=979, 1,
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 246, 2,
                       ifelse(IND1950 %in% c(246, 976), 3,
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 500, 4,
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 600, 5, 
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 700, 6,
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 800, 7,
                       ifelse(IND1950 < 900, 8, 9))))))))) %>%
          mutate(IND = factor(IND, 
                        labels = c("None", "Ag/Ext", "Const/GenLab", "Manuf",
                                    "Trans/Comm", "Trade", "FIRE", "Services", "PubAdm")))
table(ipums$IND)

        None       Ag/Ext Const/GenLab        Manuf 
     3035624       635470        95686       355962 
  Trans/Comm        Trade         FIRE     Services 
      138505       212660        35923       295631 
      PubAdm 
       36034

We can check to make sure that our recode worked the way we wanted it to by making a scatterplot of IND and IND1950 to see the relationship between the two. Since we are just checking to make sure the recode worked, we dont need to facet or weight.

qplot(IND, IND1950, data = ipums)

Now we can plot this variable the same way we plotted IND1950 above.

ipums %>% group_by(YEAR, IND, SEX) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
  ggplot(aes(YEAR, n, fill = IND)) + geom_col() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1870, 1880, 1900, 1910, 1920, 1930)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
     facet_grid(cols=vars(factor(SEX,label=c("Male", "Female"))))

    theme_minimal() +
    labs(x = "Census Year", y = "Population", fill = "Age", title = "U.S. Population by Age, 1870-1930")

Thinking Spatially

Although railroads were rapidly producing a national economy and national culture, the experience of industrializing America differed strongly by region and by race. Here we will consider region; in the lab we will also consider race. We are going to use the STATEFIP variable to assign each record to one of the four census regions: Northeast, Midwest, South, and West. For this analysis, lets eliminate Alaska, Hawaii, and any records that dont list one of the other 48 states.

The first thing we will do is make a vector of the STATEFIP codes for each region:

northeast <- c(9, 23, 25, 33, 44, 50, 34, 36, 42)
midwest <- c(17, 18, 26, 39, 55, 19, 20, 27, 29, 31, 38, 46)
south <- c(10, 11, 12, 13, 24, 37, 45, 51, 54, 1, 21, 28, 47, 5, 22, 40, 48)
west <- c(4, 8, 16, 30, 32, 35, 49, 56, 6, 41, 53)

Now we can use these vectors to create a new variable called REGION:

ipums <- ipums %>% mutate(REGION = ifelse(STATEFIP %in% northeast, 1,
                                   ifelse(STATEFIP %in% midwest, 2,
                                   ifelse(STATEFIP %in% south, 3, 
                                   ifelse(STATEFIP %in% west, 4, 0))))) %>% 
  filter(REGION>0) %>% 
  mutate(REGION = factor(REGION, labels=c("Northeast", "Midwest", "South", "West")))
table(ipums$REGION)

Northeast   Midwest     South      West 
  1363177   1586485   1533707    344559

For this week, we will focus our analysis on men aged 15-64. Create a new data frame that only includes these men, and that contains all of the variables we have made so far. Test to make sure you have done this correctly.

men <- ipums %>% filter(SEX==1 & AGE %in% 15:64)

Now make a plot with YEAR on the x-axis, number of people on the y-axis, and IND represented by fill, with facets for REGION. By default, ggplot() uses the same scales on the x- and y-axes for all facets. This enhances comparability, but in this case makes it difficult to see what is going on in the West. We can allow different y-axis scales in each facet by including the scales = "free_y" argument in the facet_wrap() function. Note that I have made the height of the graph taller with fig.height = 10 in the curly braces that start the code block.

men %>% group_by(YEAR,IND,REGION) %>% count(wt = PERWT) %>%
ggplot(aes(YEAR,n,fill=IND)) + geom_col() +
facet_wrap(vars(REGION),scales="free_y")+
scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1870,1880,1900,1910,1920,1930))+
    scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::comma)+
  theme_minimal()+
    labs(x="Census Year", y="Number of Men 15-64", fill = "Industry", title="Industry by Region for Men Aged 15-64, 1870-1930")
